    우리 임금 총명하시와
    현교(玄敎)를 통달하시어
    사지(四智)의 교화에다
    십선(十善)의 효험으로
    우리 대중을 깨우치시어
    꿈속에서 깨난 듯하구려
    우리 임금 인자하시와
    이내 방편을 베풀어
    탑과 묘(廟)를 세우시고
    백성에게 알려 주시니
    정과(正果)는 이뤄지고
    사인(邪因)은 떠나갔네
    선각(先覺)이 후각(後覺)을 깨우쳐
    원각에 오르게 하시니
    법시(法施)는 다함이 없고
    택리(澤利)는 박흡(博洽)하도다
    무엇으로 미덕을 밝히랴
    이 빗돌을 의탁하노라
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1560_010_0010&viewSync=OT
  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 현겁(賢劫) : '
    value: 불경(佛經)에, “과거의 주겁(住劫)은 장엄겁(莊嚴劫)이라 하고, 미래의 주겁(住劫)은 성숙겁(星宿劫)이라 하고, 현재의 주겁은 현겁(賢劫)이라 하는데, 현재의 주겁으로 20이 가감(加減)하는 가운데 천불(千佛)이 출세하였다. 그러므로 찬미(讚美)하며 현겁이라 한다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 오탁(五濁)의 상계(像季) : '
    value: 오탁은, 세계에 다섯 종류의 탁하고 악한 것이 있다는 말이다. 첫째로 중생탁(衆生濁)인데, 중생이 악업을 많이 지어서 인과보복을 두려워하지 않는다는 것이요, 둘째는 견탁(見濁)인데 중생이 사견(邪見)이 분둔하여 선도(善道)를 닦지 않는다는 것이요, 셋째로 번뇌탁(煩惱濁)인데, 중생이 애욕(愛慾)이 많아서 심신을 어지럽게 한다는 것이요, 넷째는 명탁(命濁)인데, 중생의 악업이 증가하여 수명이 단축한다는 것이요, 다섯째는 겁탁(劫濁)인데, 때가 감겁(減劫)을 당해서 사람의 수명이 날로 줄어들고 흉년과 질병아리 등속이 서로 계속해 일어난다는 것임. 상계(像季)는 상교(像敎)가 능이(陵夷)한 말세를 말한 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D003] 사중(四衆) : '
    value: 불가(佛家)의 용어로 사부중(四部衆)이라는 말임. 《약사경(藥師經)》에, 비구(比丘)ㆍ비구니(比丘尼)ㆍ우바새[優婆塞]ㆍ우바이[優婆夷]로 불교교단을 구성하는 4종류의 사람을 말한다.
  - key: '[주-D004] 재유(在宥) : '
    value: 《장자》에 있는 편명(篇名)인데, 그 요지는 간섭하는 것을 경계하고 방임하는 것을 주장하여 물(物)을 자유에 맡기면 일체가 다스려지지 않는 것이 없다는 것임.
  - key: '[주-D005] 금구(金口) : '
    value: 부처의 입을 말한 것임. 부처의 몸이 황금색으로 되었기 때문에 그 입을 들어 금구(金口)라 칭하고, 또 부처의 입과 혀가 금강석과 같이 견고하여 무너지지 않기 때문에 금구라 이른다 하였음. 지관보행전행결(止觀輔行傳行決)에, “여러 여래가 황금색 몸으로 구업(口業)을 기록한 바이다 [金口者 如來黃 金色身 口業所記].” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D006] 오백 …… 응하여 : '
    value: 오백 년이 되면 반드시 왕자(王者)가 일어난다는 말을 인용한 것임. 《맹자》에, “요순(堯舜)으로부터 탕(湯)에 이르기까지 오백여 년이요. 탕에서 문왕(文王)에게 이르기까지 오백여 년이라.” 하였음.
  - key: '[주-D001] 庴 : '
    value: 厝
  - key: '[주-D002] 敝 : '
    value: 敞
english:
  title: Inscription and Preface for the Great Awakening Temple of the Great Ming and Chosŏn
  author: Kim Su-on
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Consider this: in the tenth year of our sovereign's reign, the year Ǩapsin, achievement has been accomplished and governance stabilized. Ritual observance brings order, music brings harmony. The realm enjoys respite, and the people and all things flourish in peace. The sovereign's spirit ascends to the Ultimate Way, contemplating with reverent silence the Mysterious Teaching. He wishes to plant the roots of virtue together with all sentient beings across infinite ages, and together ascend to the realm of longevity. Among the three collections and twelve divisions of the Buddha's lifetime teachings, the Great Awakening Scripture alone represents the true, sudden teaching and essential doctrine. In spare moments from governing, he personally established the oral transmission, combining Chinese and vernacular so that all people might hear the Great Vehicle dharma.

    In the summer of the fourth month that year, on the day Kengsu, Prince Hyogyŏng established a stone bell at the eastern slope of Whiterock Hermitage, enshrining the Buddha's relics. A dharma assembly was convened to lecture on the Awakening Scripture. That evening, the Buddha manifested his form in the heavens; a divine monk crossed the altar; auspicious vapors filled the air, radiance shone brilliantly, sweet springs flowed abundantly, and the Buddha's relics multiplied into more than eight hundred fragments. On the day Kaphin of the fifth month, the relics were brought before the sovereign with appropriate ceremony. The sovereign and queen prostrated before the Hangyuan Hall, and the relics multiplied again into more than four hundred fragments. The hundred officials submitted congratulatory memorials, upon which an amnesty was proclaimed throughout the realm. An edict was issued to the State Council, saying: "Śākyamuni among the thousand Buddhas of the Fortunate Kalpa is the fourth; his way extends through all directions, his wisdom encompasses both realms. He expounds the dharma and delivers all beings. His teachings, transmitted to China, number eighty-four thousand volumes. Yet the Awakening Scripture is the original source of ultimate fruition. Having translated its words and revealed their meaning to circulate widely, I find my uncle Prince Hyogyŏng opening a dharma assembly where all buddhas manifest miraculous transformations of such magnitude. In this degenerate age of five corruptions, to encounter such rare phenomena—should we not restore this ancient temple and name it the Great Awakening, thereby embodying the supreme dharma-word?" The ministers bowed and prostrated, saying, "How dare we not respectfully accept your majesty's gracious command."

    The temple stood in Kyŏnghŭng District within the capital, surrounded by more than two thousand paces. When our Great Ancestor established his capital at Hanyang, this temple served as the main monastery of the Caodong school. When the order dissolved, the temple fell into disrepair, becoming government offices for nearly forty years. In the sixth month of the following year, on the day Ŭlmyo, the sovereign himself visited, surveying the location. White Peak guarded to the north, the waters flowed to the south; the position faced the sun, the land was spacious and fair—ideal for a great temple. He commanded his minister Pok and others to oversee the construction. First, they erected temporary structures at the northeastern corner and began carving the Buddha image. Suddenly, golden clouds covered the roof, celestial flowers scattered like rain, and all five colors appeared. Minister Pok rushed to report this. The sovereign received the officials' congratulations at the Hall of Diligent Governance, proclaimed an amnesty, and elevated the ranks of his hundred officials.

    On the day Kapcha of the ninth month, auspicious vapors rose from the temple's main hall, penetrating the blue sky and connecting with the Hangyuan Hall. The officials again submitted congratulatory memorials, and the sovereign proclaimed an amnesty. Workers gathered eagerly; though urged not to hurry, they labored diligently. The four communities vied to offer donations, fearing to be last. By the day Ŭlmyo of the tenth month, the work was complete. Measuring by pillars, there were more than three hundred buildings. The Buddha hall stood majestically at the center, receiving the title "Hall of Great Radiance." To the left was the meditation hall; to the right, the assembly hall. The outer gates were named the "Gate of Silent Light," the "Gate of Wisdom," and the "Gate of Liberation." The bell tower became the "Hall of Dharma Thunder," the provision facility the "Quarters of Fragrant Serenity." A pond was dug to the east, planted with lotus; gardens opened to the west, planted with flowers. Behind the main hall stood the "Hall of the Ocean Storehouse" for housing the scriptures. A thirteen-tiered pagoda was erected, enshrining the relics and the newly translated Awakening Scripture. Every hall, residence, storehouse, and kitchen stood in proper position and sequence. The plan was magnificent, gold and jade gleaming splendidly—a beauty of construction unmatched in its symmetry. Even the bells, stones, and ordinary implements were complete and abundant.

    The following year, on the eighth day of the fourth month, the sovereign commanded eminent monks from all temples to conduct a grand assembly. The newly translated Awakening Scripture was ceremonially recited as the temple was consecrated. The sovereign himself attended the dharma hall, inviting attendants, ministers, and envoys from distant lands to participate in the rites. At that moment, five-colored clouds billowed, celestial flowers fell like rain, white dragons coiled majestically, and paired cranes danced amid the clouds. Auspicious portents multiplied endlessly—all witnessed by ten thousand eyes. The sovereign specially bestowed rice and cloth on the temple monks.

    Again, the following year on the eighth day of the fourth month, with the pagoda's completion, another assembly was held and the sovereign attended. Once more came celestial flowers, auspicious vapors, and miraculous relics. White light ascended, branching into streams that stretched across the heavens, rotating into wheels, layer upon layer without end. As sunlight dimmed, monks, nuns, clergy, and laity by the millions gazed upward, bowed, and prostrated. Upon the sovereign's return to the palace, scholars, elders, and musicians all offered songs of praise. The streets filled with crowds of people singing and dancing; joy thundered like storm clouds. The sovereign proclaimed an amnesty and elevated the ranks of his hundred officials by one degree.

    The officials joined in petition, saying: "We humbly observe that you have founded a great monastery, erected a great dharma banner, and convened a great assembly. The auspicious portents have been manifold beyond number—truly unprecedented since ancient times. This reflects not merely the unfathomable spiritual transformation of Buddha and the bodhisattvas, but shows how your majesty's ultimate virtue merges with the Way, silently harmonizing with the highest vehicle. We request that this be inscribed upon stone for all eternity to behold." The sovereign summoned this minister Su-on to compose the inscription. Su-on, receiving this command with reverence and trepidation, dared not refuse.

    I humbly reflect: our sovereign possesses a heaven-bestowed sagacity surpassing all rulers of antiquity. In his former station, he perceived omens before they manifested, pacified chaos and rebellion, and received heaven's luminous mandate. Since ascending the throne, he has focused intently on governance, scarcely pausing to eat. Cultivating virtue and practicing goodness, he perfects moral transformation and straightens customs. The rains and sunshine come in season; the people know peace, harvests flourish, and perfect order is achieved. His authority extends beyond the seas. Even distant and remote lands maintain unbroken communication. The excellence of his accomplished virtue and great deeds surpasses the Three Sovereigns and Five Emperors. Yet seeing the countless people wandering in darkness through cycles of rebirth with no means of liberation, he relied on the definitive scriptures, personally expounding and translating them for easy comprehension, and distributed them throughout the realm. Within the capital, he built this great temple so that all sentient beings might draw near to the Buddha's compassion, abandon delusion, turn toward righteousness, become virtuous in custom, and together enter the ocean of the Tathāgata's omniscience. Minister and common folk alike rejoiced; people came like rushing water, drums resounded ceaselessly, and in mere months the work was completed.

    Alas! The sovereign's wise policies answer the Buddha's charge; his grace below fulfills the people's hopes. The hundred deities cooperate in harmony, heaven and earth manifest their responsiveness. Since the work began, auspicious omens have gathered, great blessing has flourished brilliantly. The universal salvation and miraculous compassion of the Awakening Buddha, the mysterious efficacy of our sovereign's utmost sincerity—how could this humble servant's limited understanding express such things? Yet having served as an attendant and witnessed these glorious accomplishments, I dare not refrain from expounding and praising them, causing this great bell to resound into endless ages. I reverently bow and compose this inscription:

    How glorious our sovereign!
    Heaven-endowed with courage and wisdom.
    Clear in perceiving omens, he pacified upheaval,
    Opened what was blocked, rescued the drowning.
    Heaven accords and people follow;
    The luminous mandate rests here.
    He governs the Great East,
    Focused and diligent in rule.
    Following the ancestors and exemplifying their ways,
    He matches the Three Sovereigns and Five Emperors.
    With reverence and caution,
    Never yielding to idleness.
    Good governance, good teaching—
    Ten years of nurturing and freeing.
    Manners grow sincere, customs refined;
    A golden age of peace is realized.

    Simple sentient beings,
    Though your nature and form are the same,
    You drift on confused paths,
    Knowing not how to escape.
    Only this Great Awakening
    Is the source of all dharmas.
    Having translated and expounded,
    Dividing chapters, analyzing verses—
    The patient teaching
    Equals the Buddha's golden words.

    When the bell was raised and the assembly convened,
    The leading prince presided.
    The true dharma blazed forth
    Like the lion's roar.
    Miracles manifested repeatedly
    And reached our sovereign.
    Our sovereign rejoiced:
    "Hear, my officials!
    The Buddha's miraculous transformation
    Is truly inconceivable.
    Encountering this rare excellence,
    What joy could compare?

    An ancient temple site
    Remained in our capital.
    Shall we not restore it,
    And spread the mystical wind?
    The layout and all arrangements
    I myself have determined.
    I commission Minister Pok
    To oversee the work.
    The people came like sons,
    And in days few, completion came.

    Halls and galleries,
    Railings and rooms—
    Like flying pheasants, soaring birds,
    Both precise and strong.
    A pagoda rises in the courtyard,
    Like the Buddha Many-Treasures appearing.
    Bells chime through emptiness;
    All beings hear and awaken.

    The great assembly opened twice;
    The sovereign's procession came twice.
    Wondrous auspices and strange portents
    Layered and mingled.
    All with eyes to see and ears to hear
    Found joy without measure.

    The four classes of this realm
    And peoples of distant lands—
    Ten thousand voices with one sound
    Called out and danced together.

    Our sovereign, divine and sage,
    Answers the five-hundred-year cycle.
    Martial valor and civil learning
    Rare since the ancient world.
    Our sovereign, wise and perceptive,
    Penetrates the mystical teaching.
    The transformation of four wisdoms,
    The fruits of ten virtues—
    He awakens our clouded multitude
    As if from dreams.

    Our sovereign, of supreme compassion,
    Dispenses means and methods:
    Building pagodas and temples,
    Making known to all people.
    Right fruition is achieved;
    Wrong causes dissolve.
    The first-awakened awakens the later-awakened;
    All ascend to perfect awakening.
    The dharma gift knows no end;
    Blessing flows boundlessly.
    How shall we make this known?
    We entrust it to this stone.
  footnotes:
    - The Fortunate Kalpa (現劫) is the current cosmic age during which one thousand buddhas will appear. Śākyamuni is the fourth of these thousand buddhas.
    - The five corruptions (五濁) of the degenerate age (像季) refer to the decline of dharma and virtue that characterizes the end-times. These corruptions manifest as corruptions of sentient beings, views, afflictions, life-span, and the kalpa itself.
    - 'The four communities (四衆) are the monastic order: monks, nuns, and lay male and female disciples.'
    - The image of the sovereign's reign as one of minimal intervention (在宥) alludes to the Daoist principle of non-action that paradoxically accomplishes all things.
    - The Buddha's golden mouth (金口) is a classical epithet for the Buddha's speech, referring both to the Buddha's golden-hued body in iconography and to the incorruptible nature of his words.
